1. e4 c5 {
This game shows WHAT IDEAS : base chess knowledge (base strategical principles) to <b>find the best move</b> in any position.

<p>HOW IDEAS - which moves execute - is tactic - tactical patterns, series of moves, lines. Richard Teichmann's famous quote that "Chess is 99% tactics" shows the importance of chess tactics. 
}
2. Nf3  {
Main idea of a chess game is the <b>pieces activity</b>. All other rules are more concrete ways how to realize this main principle.
Typical mistake is to start a <span style='font-weight:bold;color:orange;'>premature attack</span> before realizing the 3 main tasks of the <span style='font-weight:bold;color:green;'>opening</span> :
   <ol>
   <li>Develop the pieces, so pawn moves could be good only if they prepare the development of the pieces
   <li>Castle
   <li>Connect the rooks (move the queen)
   </ol>
}
d6

3. d4 cxd4 {
Strategical principle improve position of <b>least active piece</b> is visible in following moves : white defends black attacking e4 pawn.
}


4. Nxd4 Nf6  {
White has a lot of ways to <b>defend black attacking e4 pawn</b> : Nc3, Bd3, f3, Qf3. 
<ol>
<li>Nc3 or Bd3 - principle of the <b>least active piece</b> : bishop is already active; it controls long diagonal. So we need to develop knight. Nearly always we should develop knights before bishops. Second world champion Lasker stated this rule a long time ago. 
<li>NOT Qf3 at such early game stage. Developing queen is 3rd opening task after castle. Otherwise, opponent will start to attack our queen and gain some extra tempos for development.
<li>NOT f3 - we need to develop pieces.
</ol>
}
5. Nc3 a6  {
Best moves to put (develop) white bishops - <b>principle of pieces maximum activity</b>. To realize this, we need to put the pieces as forward as it possible on the board. So the white squared bishop should be placed on c4, the black squared bishop on g5.
}
6. Be3  {
Only because of concrete preparation against the opponent. 
}
e5 7. Nf3 Be7 8. Bc4 O-O

9. O-O Be6 {
This is situation when the pieces (bishops) attack each other. Strategical rule about this type of the situations is : <b>keep up pressure by not taking opponents piece</b>, because it will help an opponent to get more active position.

<p>If white takes on e6 <b>removing pressure helps the opponent a lot</b>. Why :
<ol>
<li>black opens "f" file for his rook
<li>black e6 pawn covers d5 and f5 squares, so it will not be possible to bring white the pieces there.
</ol>
}

10. Bb3 Bxb3 {
White has 2 ways to protect the bishop without taking on the e6 :
<ol>
<li>worse is Bb3, but, is made regarding to preparation for mistake black take on the b3 on the next move - <b>remove pressure</b> giving new open line for the white's rook. 
<li>better is support the bishop with Qe2. Why ?
   <ol>
   <li>finish realization of opening main tasks - connect rooks
   <li><b>principle of least active piece</b> - bishop was already developed; queen is still on the starting position
   </ol>
</ol>
}

11. axb3 Nbd7 {
<b>Black weaknesses are</b> : pawns or the squares on the 5th and on the 6th rank, which can't be protected by pawns - <b>d6 pawn and d5 square</b>. They can't be protected by any pawns, so we can attack and capture them quite easily.

<p><b>f5 square is black weakness also</b> (not as weak as d6 or d5) because of one additional idea regarding to weaknesses - f5 square can be protected by the g6 move, but it will weaken the h6 square at the same time. Sometimes, we can see the situation when opponent can make the pawn move and protect the square, but in the same time he will weaken another square in his position. This situation happens for the squares a5, b6 and f5. 

<p>After develop, castle and 12. Qe2 white has connected the rooks - white have finished main openings tasks - <span style='font-weight:bold;color:green;'>middlegame starts</span>. In the middlegame we :
<ol>
<li>compose a attack plan in 2 steps :
   <ol>
   <li>realize object of the attack - eg <b>weaknesses</b>
   <li>way how to attack
   </ol>
<li>start attack
</ol>
}

12. Qe2 Re8 {
So in this position when white is finding the objects of attack, they will be a5, b6, d6, d5, f5. How we can decide what exactly we will attack?
There is another <b>strategical principle of the center</b> - central squares are the most important on the board because the pieces in the center are the most active. Centralization provides the base idea of a chess game - the activity of the pieces. 
What do I mean regarding the center squares? Certainly these are 4 squares in the center of the board: d4, d5, e4, e5. But also quite often "center squares" mean the huge center (into the square f3-c3-c6-f6). The pieces in the huge center control the situation in the 4 central squares very well. For example, white's knight from c3 control squares d5 and e4. 
As a general conclusion, I can say that first of all we should attack the weaknesses in the center. 
In this position, the first stage of composing of a plan for white is that he needs to realize that he has to attack the d6, d5, and f5 weaknesses. 
In the second stage, we need to think about how we can use our pieces to attack these weaknesses. How can we do it? The rook should go on d1. It will put the pressure on the "d" file and attack d6 and d5. Another rook probably will be placed on the "d" file also, so we can double rooks on the "d" file. The c3 knight will be transferred on the d5 square in the future. How can we use the bishop? It should go on the g5 and put pressure on the f6 knight, which is the main defender of a d5 weakness. Regarding the f3 knight, it should go to h4 and then on the f5. 
After composing a plan, it becomes much easier for us to play, because then we know what we should do and how we should do it. 
One more practical recommendation: after finishing the main opening tasks, you should THINK FOR SOME TIME (5-20 minutes) and compose a plan. Then, you will start to make the moves quickly, but in the critical position you should think for quite a long time. 
}
13. Rfd1 {
White is starting to realize his plan. Why does white start from the rook move? The principle of the least active peace works. 
}
Qc7 {
Now white has 3 logical moves: Nd5, Bg5 and Nh4. When we have a choice, we should start to calculate the variations. After 14.Nd5 Nxd5 15.Rxd5 Nf6 black double attack the white's pieces, so it is not good. So we need to make one of 2 other moves Bg5 or Nh4.
}
14. Bg5 Rac8 15. Nh4 g6 {
After the g6 move, the position has changed for a little bit. After changes in the position, we should make corrections in our plan. Regarding the position, I mean the stable factors, which are the material and the pawn structure. When one of these factors has changed, we should make corrections in the plan. The g6 move covered the f5 square and weakened the f6 and h6 squares. Now white is going to attack the weaknesses d6, d5 and f6 (central weaknesses). How can we use our pieces to attack these weaknesses? The queen can go on d3 or on f3. Rooks should be placed on the "d" file. The c3 knight will go to d5. The h4 knight can be transferred to the d5 square, using the maneuver Nh4-g2-e3-d5. Certainly, we need to make the move of the g2 pawn first. 
}
16. g3 Bf8 {
Now white has a choice from several logical moves: Qf3, Ng2, Rd2. One of the most important principles of a chess game is a principle of attack. Attacking moves are the best. When we make attacking moves, we improve the position of our pieces and force opponent to go back, to make passive defensive moves. Attacking moves help us to realize our plan, and they don't allow our opponent to realize his plan at the same time. This is an ideal situation. In any position, first, we should try to make attacking moves.
}
17. Qf3 {
You can see that it is very easy to find the right moves with the right system of thinking, because typically we have just one or two possible attacking moves, and we can easily make one of them. Right now white has 2 possible attacking moves: Nd5 and Qf3. But Nd5 doesn't work, because of 17.Nd5 Nxd5 18.Rxd5 Qxc2, so we should play Qf3.
}
Bg7 {
Which move should white play now? The most aggressive move again! Ng2 is good, but Rd2 following by Rad1 will be the best, because it will attack black's position.
}
18. Rd2 h6 19. Bxf6 Nxf6 20. Rad1 Rcd8 21. Ng2 Qe7 22. Ne3 Qe6 23. Nc4 {
Attack again! Force black to go back. This is the situation which I have told you before. White's attacking move Nc4 helps white to increase the knight's activity and force black to decrease the bishop's activity at the same time. That's why attacking moves are the best.
}
Bf8 24. Nd5 Nxd5 25. Rxd5 Qc8 {
Black wants to take the c2 pawn at the end of the line 26.Nxd6 Bxd6 27.Rxd6 Rxd6 28.Rxd6 Qxc2. White can solve this problem easily though.
}
26. Qd3 {
This is also an attacking move. White wants to make the Ne5 move, using the weakness of a d8 rook. 
}
Be7 27. c3 Qc6 {
Again white can't win the pawn, because of 28.Nxd6 Bxd6 29.Rxd6 Rxd6 30.Qxd6 Qxe4.
}
28. f3 h5 {
White still can't take Nxd6, because of 29.Nxd6 Qb6+ 30.Kg2 Bxd6 31.Rxd6 Rxd6 32.Qxd6 Qxb3. Black all the time tries to find tactical tricks, but since white's position is strategically winning, he should solve these problems easily. 
}
29. Kg2 Kf8 30. Nxd6 Bxd6 31. Rxd6 Rxd6 32. Qxd6+ Qxd6 33. Rxd6 {
White has successfully realized the middlegame plan. Now we can see an endgame position. As I told before, every stage of the game has some special properties. In the endgame we also need to compose a plan. Since in the endgame we usually can't attack the king, the plan will be different, compared to the middlegame. In the endgame, the biggest value is the pawns. The pawn structure determines the plan. There are 2 main plans for an endgame:
1) Advance your passed pawns to promote them into a new queen.
2) Attack the opponent's weak pawns. 
For example, in this position, white's plan will be to use his pawn majority on the queen-side to create the passed pawn on the "c" file (where the pawn has no counterpart); and to attack black's weak pawns. The weakest ones are the backwards pawns at b7 and f7, so white is going to combine these 2 plans and realize both of them. 
}
Re7 34. Kf2 {
Principle of the least active piece works. In the endgame, the king should be in the center. 
}
Rc7 35. Ke3 Ke7 36. Rb6 {
Principle of maximum of activity works. We should make the moves of the pieces as forward as possible. Certainly, white should not go back.
}
Rd7 37. f4 {
In the endgame, the active side should make the moves of the pawns forward. The pawns will be closer to the 8th rank, and they will fix the opponent's weaknesses. 
}
exf4+ 38. gxf4 Kd8 39. b4 Kc7 40. Rf6 Kd8 41. h4 Ke7 42. Rb6 Kf8 43. e5 Ke8
44. Ke4 Kf8 45. f5 gxf5+ 46. Kxf5 Kg7 {
